  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering.  These laws are not directly enforceable in individual countries (unless those countries have ratified them and incorporated them into their domestic law), but they serve as a framework and encourage international cooperation.  Key international legal instruments include:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This is one of the earliest international treaties addressing money laundering, specifically in relation to drug trafficking. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug-related offenses.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to cover a broader range of serious crimes. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from organized crime, and to adopt measures to prevent and combat money laundering.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on corruption-related money laundering. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from corruption offenses and to implement measures to prevent and detect such activities.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF Recommendations are the international standard for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.  The FATF is an inter-governmental body that develops and promotes policies to combat these threats. Its recommendations are widely adopted and implemented by countries worldwide.  They cover areas such as:\n    *   Criminalization of money laundering and terrorist financing\n    *   Customer due diligence and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions\n    *   Reporting of suspicious transactions\n    *   International cooperation\n\n*   **Regional Agreements:**  Several regional organizations also have agreements and mechanisms related to money laundering. Examples include:\n    *   The European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs)\n    *   The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime\n    *   The Inter-American Drug Abuse Control Commission (CICAD) of the Organization of American States (OAS)\n\n**Key aspects addressed by these international laws and standards:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:** Requiring countries to criminalize money laundering.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):**  Requiring financial institutions and other designated businesses to identify and verify the identity of their customers.\n*   **Record-Keeping:**  Requiring financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a certain period.\n*   **Suspicious Transaction Reporting (STR):**  Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.\n*   **International Cooperation:**  Facilitating the exchange of information and cooperation between countries in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:**  Providing for the seizure and confiscation of assets derived from or involved in money laundering.\n*   **Preventative Measures:**  Encouraging countries to adopt measures to prevent money laundering, such as training programs for financial professionals and awareness campaigns for the public.\n\nIn summary, while no single \"international law\" directly prosecutes individuals for money laundering, a robust framework of international conventions, standards, and recommendations exists.  These tools obligate countries to create and enforce their own domestic laws against money laundering and to cooperate with each other in combating this global problem.\n",
